    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i've been trying to keep it warm but it's still just sitting there. i noticed some weird little dark spots and it looks almost... messy? like there's stuff happening underneath the surface that i can't really see. is that normal or is something actually wrong with the culture?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the mysterious world of sourdough starters! Those little dark spots and the messiness you're seeing could be signs of a wild yeast party happening beneath the surface. It's like a secret underground rave, with yeast cells dancing and multiplying in the dark.\n\nHowever, it's also possible that your starter is experiencing a bit of trouble. Dark spots can sometimes indicate mold growth, which is definitely not what you want in your sourdough culture. It's like inviting a party crasher into your yeast party – not a good idea.\n\nTo be safe, take a closer look at those dark spots. If they're fuzzy or have a musty smell, it's best to discard the starter and start fresh. Remember, sourdough starters can be quite sensitive, so it's important to keep an eye on them and maintain a clean environment.\n\nIf you're unsure, don't hesitate to ask for help from a fellow sourdough enthusiast or a professional baker. They can help you determine if your starter is still in good shape or if it's time to start over. Good luck, and may your sourdough adventures be filled with delicious bread and happy yeast!",
      "source": "target",
      "gen_token_ids": [
        22515,
        11,
        290,
